sect2.para:
Individuals with BDD
            BDD
          have excessive and persistent concerns related to perceived flaws in physical appearance that appear minimal or non-existent to others (Jassi & Krebs, 
            2023
         ). Facial features (e. g., nose, eyes, hair) are the most common areas of preoccupation, but worries can center on physical features of any body part. Similar to OCD, those with BDD engage in repetitive behaviors, such as checking, grooming, and camouflaging, to attempt to correct or conceal the perceived flaw. Avoidance of social situations and mental rituals (e. g., comparing their physical features to others) is also common. BDD is distinct from OCD because rituals are narrowly focused on attempts to correct perceived problems in appearance and not on other obsessions/compulsions related to common OCD content themes (e. g., contamination, responsibility for harm). Patients with BDD typically have poor insight and are convinced that there is an actual flaw in their physical appearance. The DSM-5-TR includes insight as a specifier for BDD, and studies demonstrate that insight can improve with treatment (Harrison et al.,
            2016
         ). Additionally, BDD is underdiagnosed because individuals with the condition may not disclose concerns related to appearance due to embarrassment, individuals tend to seek help from dermatologists and cosmetic surgeons before seeking mental health treatment, and individuals are misdiagnosed with other psychiatric conditions (e. g., social anxiety disorder, OCD). Finally, BDD is associated with higher rates of suicide attempts, as individuals with BDD are 2.6 times more likely to engage in suicide attempts compared to those without BDD (Angelakis et al.,
            2016
         ).

The most comprehensive assessment for hoarding disorder is the Structured Interview for Hoarding Disorder (Nordsletten et al.,
            2013
         )—a semi-structured, clinician-administered interview that evaluates all six DSM-5-TR criteria for hoarding disorder. This assessment also includes risk assessment associated with hoarding behaviors (e. g., fire hazards, unhygienic conditions) and questions to facilitate differential diagnoses (e. g., autism spectrum disorder, OCD). Ideally, assessment should include direct observation of the individual’s living spaces and information gathered
            gathered
         from collateral sources (e. g., family members), as patients with hoarding disorder often have low insight into their condition. If it is not possible to directly observe the individual’s living spaces, a standardized tool such as the Clutter Image Rating (Frost et al.,
            2008
         ) can be used. It is also important that assessment includes a thorough evaluation of medical history and psychopathology to rule out other potential causes.
